Welcome! In this experiment, you will play a game where you use tools and combine ingredients to make new items.

The game interface is shown below. It has an inventory of items, a crafting area, and a progress bar.

You can combine any two items by clicking and dragging them into the crafting area...

...then dropping one on top of the other.

Each item is either a tool or an ingredient. Tools have grey backgrounds and ingredients have white backgrounds. Tools can be used as many times as you want, but ingredients can only be used once.

"}, "control": {}}

metadata_:
{"time_taken": 19.112, "platform": "Chrome 141.0.0.0 on Windows 10 64-bit", "download_speed_megabits_per_sec": 10, "event_log": [{"eventType": "trialConstruct", "localTime": "2025-10-28T18:59:52.212Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialPrepare", "localTime": "2025-10-28T18:59:52.220Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialStart", "localTime": "2025-10-28T18:59:52.220Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "responseEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T18:59:52.225Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "submitEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T18:59:52.225Z", "info": null}], "prompt": {"text": "

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

CONSENT

DESCRIPTION: You are invited to participate in a research study on human learning and communication. You will be asked to play a game and possibly send messages to other participants about the game.

TIME INVOLVEMENT: Your participation will take approximately 30 minutes.

RISKS AND BENEFITS: If you communicate personally-identifiable information to another participant, then the researchers and recipient of the message will have that information. It is possible that information study data could be leaked in a data breach. Study data will be stored securely, in compliance with Stanford University standards, minimizing the risk of confidentiality breach. We cannot and do not guarantee or promise that you will receive any benefits from this study.

PAYMENTS: You will receive $7 as payment for your participation, as well as a bonus of up to $1 depending on your performance.

PARTICIPANT'S RIGHTS: If you have read this form and have decided to participate in this project, please understand your participation is voluntary and you have the right to withdraw your consent or discontinue participation at any time without penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. The alternative is not to participate. You have the right to refuse to answer particular questions. The results of this research study may be presented at scientific or professional meetings or published in scientific journals. Your individual privacy will be maintained in all published and written data resulting from the study.

PRIVACY AND CONFIDENTIALITY: The risks associated with this study are minimal. Study data will be stored securely, in compliance with Stanford University standards, minimizing the risk of confidentiality breach. Your individual privacy will be maintained during the research and in all published and written data resulting from the study.

CONTACT INFORMATION:

Questions: If you have any questions, concerns or complaints about this research, its procedures, risks and benefits, contact Ben Prystawski ( benpry@stanford.edu) or the Protocol Director, Noah Goodman (ngoodman@stanford.edu).

Independent Contact: If you are not satisfied with how this study is being conducted, or if you have any concerns, complaints, or general questions about the research or your rights as a participant, please contact the Stanford Institutional Review Board (IRB) to speak to someone independent of the research team at 650-723-2480 or toll free at 1-866-680-2906, or email at irbnonmed@stanford.edu. You can also write to the Stanford IRB, Stanford University, 1705 El Camino Real, Palo Alto, CA 94306.

Please save or print a copy of this page for your records.

If you agree to participate in this research, please click "I agree" below.

metadata_:
{"time_taken": 71.487, "platform": "Chrome 142.0.0.0 on Windows 10 64-bit", "download_speed_megabits_per_sec": 10, "event_log": [{"eventType": "trialConstruct", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:15:12.206Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialPrepare", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:15:12.227Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialStart", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:15:12.227Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "responseEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:15:12.233Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "submitEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:15:12.233Z", "info": null}], "prompt": {"text": "

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

{"time_taken": 107.729, "platform": "Chrome 141.0.0.0 on OS X 10.15.7 64-bit", "download_speed_megabits_per_sec": 10, "event_log": [{"eventType": "trialConstruct", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:19:12.066Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialPrepare", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:19:12.069Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialStart", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:19:12.069Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "responseEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:19:12.074Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "submitEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T19:19:12.074Z", "info": null}], "prompt": {"text": "

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

Welcome! In this experiment, you will play a game where you use tools and combine ingredients to make new items.

The game interface is shown below. It has an inventory of items, a crafting area, and a progress bar.

You can combine any two items by clicking and dragging them into the crafting area...

...then dropping one on top of the other.

Each item is either a tool or an ingredient. Tools have grey backgrounds and ingredients have white backgrounds. Tools can be used as many times as you want, but ingredients can only be used once.

metadata_:
{"time_taken": 23.523, "platform": "Chrome 141.0.0.0 on Windows 10 64-bit", "download_speed_megabits_per_sec": 10, "event_log": [{"eventType": "trialConstruct", "localTime": "2025-10-28T20:43:39.626Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialPrepare", "localTime": "2025-10-28T20:43:39.661Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "trialStart", "localTime": "2025-10-28T20:43:39.662Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "responseEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T20:43:39.666Z", "info": null}, {"eventType": "submitEnable", "localTime": "2025-10-28T20:43:39.666Z", "info": null}], "prompt": {"text": "

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

answer:
Refine objects and combine them.  Don't combine frames with hard objects.  Don't put too many things together as it overcomplicates.
2 cut soft combined+framed generally gives a high score, but avoid yarn+ribbon.

question: message
answer:
The 2 same states of matter with one magical and one mundane and then vial was best I got. Only combine 2 items. If the value is still low after combining+vialing, try filtering.
Don't filter solids on their own. Don't filter ghost vapor, most others were fine.

question: post_experiment_survey
answer: {"strategy": "I tested out various combinations and tried to make a mental note, though thinking back I should have been writing EVERYTHING down. First I tried combining the base items, and then added the actions after to see how that worked. You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

You will play the game for several rounds. In each round, you will have the same tools, but different starting ingredients. As you play the game, you will learn the rules that determine how items combine and how valuable each item is. These rules might be intuitive, but they might also be unintuitive, so you should try different combinations and see what happens.

Your score in each round will be the value of the most valuable item you created. For example, if you had the two items below in your inventory, your score would be 16.

Your score can't go below 0, even if all of your items have negative values. The maximum possible score is 100 in every round You will earn a bonus of up to $1 based on your performance.

Ingredients all have features that determine how they combine with other ingredients and how valuable they are. These features change when you apply tools or combine them with other ingredients. You can see an ingredient's features by hovering over it with your mouse.

You can take notes throughout the experiment using the scratchpad on the right side of the screen. The text in the scratchpad will stay from round to round.

It is possible that one of your items might get stuck somewhere where you can't click it. If this happens, you can refresh the page and your inventory will be preserved.

When you are ready, click the "Start" button to play a practice game.

"}, "control": {}}

*Short Guide To Combining Ingredient's* 
Solids combine with vial
Liquids combine with filter
Gas/ Vapor combine with filter
Combine the same type of ingredients together
(Example: Liquid magical + Liquid magical= New Item)

Some ingredients can combine even if one is a solid, liquid or gas as long as its the same type.
(Example: Solid mundane + vial = Mundane vial and 
Gas mundane + filter = gas filtered. Mundane vial + Gas Mundane= 100% Item

Combine two filtered or two vial ingredients together to get a 100% item! Good luck y'all!

answer:
I was able to achieve 100 a couple of times, if you get two dragon parts, add vial separately, then combine them

If you see sun stone and obsidian, apply vial separately, then combine

If it seems like you can filter two separate items (eg vapor or dew), filter them both separately, then combine, I was able to achieve 100 one time as well
